## Security Considerations

`secret_data` is a write-only attribute (Terraform 1.11+). The plaintext is never written to Terraform state. To rotate the value, change `secret_data` and increment `secret_data_version` — the version counter is what Terraform diffs against, since write-only values cannot be compared directly.

## Scopes

`scopes` declares which features may consume the secret. The dataplane API enforces scope-based access — supplying a scope that doesn't match the consumer (e.g. setting only `SCOPE_REDPANDA_CONNECT` and trying to reference the secret from a `redpanda_shadow_link`) will cause the consumer to fail at runtime. Multiple scopes can be combined.

| Scope | Used by |
|---|---|
| `SCOPE_REDPANDA_CLUSTER` | `redpanda_shadow_link` (SCRAM/PLAIN passwords, TLS keys) |
| `SCOPE_REDPANDA_CONNECT` | `redpanda_pipeline` |
| `SCOPE_MCP_SERVER` | MCP server resources |
| `SCOPE_AI_AGENT` | AI agent resources |
| `SCOPE_AI_GATEWAY` | AI gateway resources |

## Labels

The dataplane API auto-injects a managed `owner` label (e.g. `owner=console`). User-supplied labels are merged in at create time and round-trip through state. Per the API, labels are immutable on Update — to change them you must destroy and recreate the secret.

## Import

```shell
terraform import {{.Name}}.example secretName,clusterId
```

Where `secretName` is the secret's identifier (uppercase, matching `^[A-Z][A-Z0-9_]*$`) and `clusterId` is the ID of the cluster in Redpanda Cloud. After import, `secret_data` is unset until the next apply provides a value.

